{"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "schema", "document", "Document"], "kwargs": {"metadata": {"producer": "Adobe PDF Library 17.0", "creator": "Adobe InDesign 19.5 (Macintosh)", "creationdate": "2025-06-30T13:23:51+01:00", "moddate": "2025-06-30T13:23:54+01:00", "trapped": "/False", "source": "corpus\\autistic-spectrum-v4.pdf", "total_pages": 47, "page": 26, "page_label": "27"}, "page_content": "27\n\u2022 My teacher will stay with me and my class. She will remind us that there is not really \na fire (who will look after me, addressing worry)\n\u2022 We will wait outside for a few minutes until my teacher is told we can go back to \nclass. If I have worries, I can try to tell my teacher, she will try to help me. I can \nsqueeze my squishy ball. (duration, person to help me, coping strategy)\n\u2022 Each time there is a fire drill, every class leaves the school building the same way. \nThey go to the same special safe area outside of the building. (what I can expect, \nlocation)\n\u2022 Fire drills help teachers and students practice leaving the building calmly, quickly, \nand safely. (reason given)\nHere are some examples where using a Social Story can be helpful:\n\u2022 It\u2019s ok to make mistakes\n\u2022 If the answer is \u201cno\u201d\n\u2022 Please \u2018hurry up\u2019\n\u2022 Telling my teacher about a problem\n\u2022 Staying calm with difficult schoolwork\n\u2022 How to take a shower\n\u2022 Personal hygiene\n\u2022 (See The New Social Story Book by Carol Gray)", "type": "Document"}}